<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="271" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[811,1457,981,1581]" box="[813,903,981,1007]" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">REMARK</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[811,1457,981,1581]" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">
Originally identified as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="A.Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1833" box="[1061,1269,1012,1038]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Scotophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dinganii">
<emphasis box="[1061,1269,1012,1038]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">Scotophilus dinganii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(A. Smith, 1833) due to its bright yellow ventral side side and its forearm length of 
<quantity box="[842,947,1076,1103]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.779999999999999" pageId="20" pageNumber="271" unit="mm" value="57.8">57.8 mm</quantity>
, the West African form, which also occurs in western 
<collectingCountry box="[900,970,1109,1135]" name="Kenya" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">Kenya</collectingCountry>
, has been recently renamed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Brooks &amp; Bickham" authorityYear="2014" box="[1256,1393,1108,1134]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Scotophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="livingstonii">
<emphasis box="[1256,1393,1108,1134]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">S. livingstonii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on phylogenetic and morphological distinct 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="A.Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1833" box="[1290,1406,1140,1166]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Scotophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dinganii">
<emphasis box="[1290,1406,1140,1166]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">S. dinganii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-like clades (
<bibRefCitation author="BROOKS D. M. &amp; BICKHAM J. W." box="[891,1159,1172,1198]" pageId="20" pageNumber="271" pagination="1 - 21" refId="ref17332" refString="BROOKS D. M. &amp; BICKHAM J. W. 2014. - New Species of Scotophilus (Chiroptera: Vespertilionidae) from Sub-Saharan Africa. Occasional Papers Museum Texas Tech University 326: 1 - 21." type="journal article" year="2014">Brooks &amp; Bickham 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Our specimen was caught in a net set across the Agumatsa River flanked by secondary forest and nearby small cassava fields. Other Ghana-Togo Highlands specimens are known from Odomi Jongo, 12 Miles E Nkwanta in 
<collectingCountry box="[966,1038,1299,1325]" name="Ghana" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">Ghana</collectingCountry>
(USNM 424888) and from Atakpamé and Ezimé in 
<collectingCountry box="[969,1025,1332,1358]" name="Togo" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">Togo</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="ROBBINS C. B." box="[1043,1201,1331,1357]" pageId="20" pageNumber="271" pagination="83 - 88" refId="ref22161" refString="ROBBINS C. B. 1980. - Small mammals of Togo and Benin. I. Chiroptera. Mammalia 44: 83 - 88." type="journal article" year="1980">Robbins 1980</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="ROBBINS C. B. &amp; DE VREE F. &amp; VAN CAKENBERGHE V." box="[1218,1439,1331,1358]" pageId="20" pageNumber="271" pagination="51 - 84" refId="ref22219" refString="ROBBINS C. B., DE VREE F. &amp; VAN CAKENBERGHE V. 1985. - A systematic revision of the African bat genus Scotophilus (Vespertilionidae). Zoologische Wetenschappen 246: 51 - 84." type="journal article" year="1985">
Robbins 
<emphasis box="[1319,1373,1331,1357]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">et al.</emphasis>
1985
</bibRefCitation>
). The species was also caught at three locations on the Accra Plains (
<bibRefCitation author="DECHER J." box="[892,1044,1395,1421]" pageId="20" pageNumber="271" pagination="129 - 142" refId="ref17648" refString="DECHER J. 1997 a. - Bat community patterns on the Accra Plains of Ghana, West Africa. Zeitschrift fur Saugetierkunde 62: 129 - 142." type="journal article" year="1997">Decher 1997a</bibRefCitation>
and USNM, as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="A.Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1833" box="[1218,1332,1395,1421]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Scotophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dinganii">
<emphasis box="[1218,1332,1395,1421]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">S. dinganii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and seems to be most commonly associated with 
<collectingCountry box="[1230,1309,1427,1453]" name="Guinea-Bissau" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">Guinea</collectingCountry>
savanna, forest savanna mosaic, and high forest edge. Records from 
<collectingCountry name="Ivory Coast" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">Côte d’Ivoire</collectingCountry>
are all from the northern tree savanna (
<bibRefCitation author="FAHR J." box="[1312,1422,1491,1517]" pageId="20" pageNumber="271" refId="ref18510" refString="FAHR J. 1996. - Die Chiroptera der Elfenbeinkuste (unter Berucksichtigung des westafrikanischen Raumes): Taxonomie, Habitatpraferenzen und Lebensgemeinschaften. Diplomarbeit, Julius-Maximilians-Universitat, Wurzburg. 204 p." type="book" year="1996">Fahr 1996</bibRefCitation>
, as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="A.Smith" baseAuthorityYear="1833" box="[813,927,1523,1549]" class="Mammalia" family="Vespertilionidae" genus="Scotophilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chiroptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="271" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dinganii">
<emphasis box="[813,927,1523,1549]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="271">S. dinganii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). This species also seems to adapt to rooftops and thatched huts for its roosts.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
